Seeing and photographing the cliff-nesting colonies of seabirds was one of the greatest experiences of my life. We were there June 13-17, but I kept a running list rather than daily lists (there would have been much duplication if I had), and so chose the middle date to make this single entry. The seabirds were essentially uncountable, and I was there for the experience more than for making counts, which the guides would be doing anyway. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709619	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			1			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-16	07:30:00	On our third day the leaders consulted and decided that birds had been coming too easily. In order for our group to fully appreciate the wonders of seeking birds on Attu, we would need to ensure that we had one day without a big chase, one day without a fantastic Siberian vagrant, one slow day. Today was that day. It is a lot of work to find birds of Attu and to have another day where rarities kept falling in our laps would be to miss out on the feeling of hard work that is so rewarding. WEATHER: The weather was nothing short of perfect and many of us birded much of the day in short sleeves. The little bit of wind that picked up was just enough to keep it from being downright hot. Many of us got to explore farther than we had in previous days, with some groups reaching Blue Robin Canyon far to the south and others reaching Gilbert Ridge up to the north. The birds seen actually included some nice finds. New for our 2006 Attu list were Common Loon, Red-necked and Horned grebes, White-winged Scoter, and Pacific Golden-Plover. Repeat rarities included Spotted Redshank and Wood Sandpiper, as well as Gray-tailed Tattler, Eurasian Wigeon, White Wagtail, and Thick-billed Murre. Several people were able to add these species to their life lists today. My group enjoyed a group of passerines hopping about on a rusty cart. All five commonly breeding songbirds (not counting Common Raven) were feeding together on the edge of this cart: Gray-crowned Rosy-Finch, Snow Bunting, Lapland Longspur, Song Sparrow, and a seemingly out-of-place Winter Wren. OTHER FAUNA: MAMMALS: Minke Whale; Harbor Seal; Sea Otter.	Casco Cove	obs34603	Marshall	Iliff	S3588711	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419986	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709560	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Ettienne Bay	L498125	H	52.9220479	172.6477432	2006-09-20	19:30:00	After enjoying the stint we hoofed it back to the boat and motored west to Etienne Bay. Thede Tobish had suggested to the team of leaders that we try Etienne as an alternate location to land. Since we had spent nearly a week in the Massacre Bay area we were happy for a change of pace, especially since Etienne was at the far southwestern tip and closer to arriving Asian birds Ettienne also had the allure of being unexplored by birders, so we were eager to put the place on the birding map. The trip west was fairly uneventful for seabirds, although I thoroughly enjoyed seeing a Parasitic Jaeger chase a Peregrine Falcon, then seeing the tables turn as the Peregrine chased the jaeger, and then seeing it switch again. One highlight as we entered Ettienne was a Whiskered Auklet that Steve Heinl spotted, which is known from just 2 prior Attu records. Ettienne Bay was fascinating in that the composition of seabirds was totally unlike that at Massacre Bay. Least Auklets were common in the mouth (we had none off Massacre). The eiders at Ettienne were mostly males, while in Massacre females predominated. And finally, we had loons: several species of loons. Steve Heinl (again) spotted a breeding plumaged Yellow-billed Loon at a distance but we motored slowly up to it and everyone got good looks. A second first-summer Yellow-billed was seen as well. And later, while the leaders scouted the shore for possible landing sites and birding areas, three Arctic Loons (adult and two juveniles) were spotted as well (I saw these well through the scope with Steve Heinl). When the birds were called into the ship only a few people were able to find these distant loons, but still, the different bird composition held exciting possibilities for the day that followed. L418947	H	52.908902	173.0044556	2006-09-15	07:30:00	Our second full day on Attu, this was our first day exploring the Massacre Bay/Coast Guard Station area. One team of 35 checked the Casco Cove and Murder Point area; another team worked Peaceful River, the runways, and the coast guard station, and a third team hiked the Henderson River valley. An additional team of two leader scouts (me and Dave Wolf) checked out Alexai Point, where little seemed to have changed from the previous day and the rare birds were actually scarcer. Their most exciting find was a single Painted Lady (butterfly), which is known from southeast Alaska but has not have occurred in the Aleutians before. Sometime around 9:30 a Tringa sandpiper flew over the wagtail group giving a mellow, two-noted call. Thede Tobish, who has the most western Alaska experience of any birder on the ship, quickly called the ID | Spotted Redshank!  This was a classic Attu experience, with teams of people assembling on a rare bird and maneuvering to get good views for everyone, although it took many hours to locate and assemble around the bird. Spotted Redshank is a rare migrant in the western Aleutians, primarily in spring where the Attu high count is four. Attu has but one previous fall record, from 26 Sep 2000. It has turned up rarely across the United States, in places like California, Massachusetts, and New Jersey, but is predictably seen only in Alaska. This was what we came here for. The grand Henderson Marsh stomp turned up other goodies as well. Chief among them was Wood Sandpiper, another rare Asian shorebird that was a life bird for most of the group. An eclipse-plumaged Eurasian Wigeon landed in Smew Pond with the redshank at one point, and a good number of Common Snipe (the Eurasian species recently split from Wilsons Snipe) were flushed by the various parties.  WEATHER: The weather today was, if anything, too nice. Sunny, temperatures in the upper 50s and low 60s, with very little wind. OTHER FAUNA: LEPS: PAINTED LADY - 1 (photo; first ever for Aleutians!). URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709752	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-19	07:30:00	Today was our last full day covering the greater Coast Guard station area and our three groups divided up to cover the three major sections. The morning was rather wet, and there were periods of wind and rain that almost recalled the weather that had been predicted for Attu. To be sure, our group was incredibly lucky for the wonderful weather conditions during our time there. The Spotted Redshank was again in position at Smew Pond, and it seemed to have gotten used to our presence and allowed closer approach | a welcome change from its first day when it would flush at almost any distance. There clearly was an arrival of Sharp-tailed Sandpipers overnight, possibly migrant birds that were grounded by the inclement weather. The Smew Pond group had four Sharp-taileds, including at least a couple that literally "dropped from the sky" in front of them. Along Debris Beach we found three Sharp-taileds together at about 9:00 and found the birds to be incredibly approachable. After prolonged scope views at 100 feet we closed the distance to about 20 feet while the birds unconcernedly foraged on the upper part of the beach. As we moved down the beach a fourth Sharp-tailed appeared and joined the other three, and later in the day their number had swollen to seven. Photographers had a field day with these birds, which remained just as confiding throughout the day. Two groups had single Pectoral Sandpipers, and some people got to study both species in the same day, comparing the brighter plumage, mostly unstreaked breasts, and streaked undertails coverts of the Sharpies.  OTHER FAUNA: MAMMALS: Minke Whale; Harbor Seal; Sea Otter.		obs34603	Marshall	Iliff	S3588714	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419989	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709714	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-18	07:30:00	Today got off to an early good start as well. Before most groups had even loaded Larry Balch called from Navy Town asking, "Does anyone want to see a Snowy Owl?" The Spotted Redshank was feeding in its "usual" spot and seemed to have become accustomed to groups of tourists gawking at it. We watched it spend about five minutes trying to swallow an oversized minnow that seemed to be stuck in its gullet. We were worried we might have to administer emergency care, but eventually the fish was swallowed and we can report that our redshank did live to see another day. Another massive rarity chase was set in motion when we glanced through the mist and fog to the back side of Smew Pond where a mid-sized shorebird was foraging. It turned out to be a juvenile Sharp-tailed Sandpiper, an Asian species that we had expected to see before this and which we began to worry that we would miss. Sharp-taileds are uncommon migrants throughout western Alaska, and can even be found predictably in the Pacific Northwest states during September and October, but which is accidental elsewhere in the country. It was a welcome lifer for much of the ship and so groups started converging on Smew Pond. Almost everyone got the bird immediately, but when one of the last groups arrived we had a bit of a scare. The Sharp-tailed flew upriver and was lost from sight for about 20 minutes. We tried to carefully walk the riverbed to flush the bird again and others of us carefully scanned the pond edge in case it had returned to its favored spots. Even when we knew where it was the Sharp-tailed had been very difficult to spot, and continuously moved in and out of the grasses at the edge. Perhaps it was not surprising then that the bird was missed. I had been the appointed riverwalker, and when I reached the pond I decided to try playing its call since it had earlier shown some level of tape response. As soon as I keyed up the iPod a shorebird started flying directly for me from the far side of the pond. It turned out to be the Sharp-tailed and on its return visit it gave great looks to the worried recent arrivals and lifted a great burden from the leaders' shoulders. We spent a long time absorbing its key field marks, which sunk in especially well for those of us that had carefully studied similar Pectoral Sandpipers in previous days. Several groups undertook ambitious afternoon walks. My group headed up Henderson Valley to Bird Canyon and Lake Elwood. Lake Elwood produced another new bird for the trip: an American Wigeon. This was perhaps the only time that I had seen Eurasian Wigeon (2) outnumber American (1), and it was one of the better comparative studies I have had. The gray head of the American contrasted markedly with its breast (little to no contrast on Eurasian). Almost on command, the American rose out of the water and flapped, revealing its diagnostic white underwing. Our other neat find on that long walk was a second Snowy Owl, this one a pure white adult sitting high on the rocky cliffs of Terrible Mountain. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844456	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-19	07:30:00	Today was our last full day covering the greater Coast Guard station area and our three groups divided up to cover the three major sections. The morning was rather wet, and there were periods of wind and rain that almost recalled the weather that had been predicted for Attu. To be sure, our group was incredibly lucky for the wonderful weather conditions during our time there. The Spotted Redshank was again in position at Smew Pond, and it seemed to have gotten used to our presence and allowed closer approach | a welcome change from its first day when it would flush at almost any distance. There clearly was an arrival of Sharp-tailed Sandpipers overnight, possibly migrant birds that were grounded by the inclement weather. The Smew Pond group had four Sharp-taileds, including at least a couple that literally "dropped from the sky" in front of them. Along Debris Beach we found three Sharp-taileds together at about 9:00 and found the birds to be incredibly approachable. After prolonged scope views at 100 feet we closed the distance to about 20 feet while the birds unconcernedly foraged on the upper part of the beach. As we moved down the beach a fourth Sharp-tailed appeared and joined the other three, and later in the day their number had swollen to seven. Photographers had a field day with these birds, which remained just as confiding throughout the day. Two groups had single Pectoral Sandpipers, and some people got to study both species in the same day, comparing the brighter plumage, mostly unstreaked breasts, and streaked undertails coverts of the Sharpies.  OTHER FAUNA: MAMMALS: Minke Whale; Harbor Seal; Sea Otter.		obs162787	Steven	Heinl	S10875072	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419989	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844254	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			1			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-16	07:30:00	On our third day the leaders consulted and decided that birds had been coming too easily. In order for our group to fully appreciate the wonders of seeking birds on Attu, we would need to ensure that we had one day without a big chase, one day without a fantastic Siberian vagrant, one slow day. Today was that day. It is a lot of work to find birds of Attu and to have another day where rarities kept falling in our laps would be to miss out on the feeling of hard work that is so rewarding. WEATHER: The weather was nothing short of perfect and many of us birded much of the day in short sleeves. The little bit of wind that picked up was just enough to keep it from being downright hot. Many of us got to explore farther than we had in previous days, with some groups reaching Blue Robin Canyon far to the south and others reaching Gilbert Ridge up to the north. The birds seen actually included some nice finds. New for our 2006 Attu list were Common Loon, Red-necked and Horned grebes, White-winged Scoter, and Pacific Golden-Plover. Repeat rarities included Spotted Redshank and Wood Sandpiper, as well as Gray-tailed Tattler, Eurasian Wigeon, White Wagtail, and Thick-billed Murre. Several people were able to add these species to their life lists today. My group enjoyed a group of passerines hopping about on a rusty cart. All five commonly breeding songbirds (not counting Common Raven) were feeding together on the edge of this cart: Gray-crowned Rosy-Finch, Snow Bunting, Lapland Longspur, Song Sparrow, and a seemingly out-of-place Winter Wren. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844246	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Island (Aleutian Is.)	L418947	H	52.908902	173.0044556	2006-09-15	07:30:00	Our second full day on Attu, this was our first day exploring the Massacre Bay/Coast Guard Station area. One team of 35 checked the Casco Cove and Murder Point area; another team worked Peaceful River, the runways, and the coast guard station, and a third team hiked the Henderson River valley. An additional team of two leader scouts (me and Dave Wolf) checked out Alexai Point, where little seemed to have changed from the previous day and the rare birds were actually scarcer. Their most exciting find was a single Painted Lady (butterfly), which is known from southeast Alaska but has not have occurred in the Aleutians before. Sometime around 9:30 a Tringa sandpiper flew over the wagtail group giving a mellow, two-noted call. Thede Tobish, who has the most western Alaska experience of any birder on the ship, quickly called the ID | Spotted Redshank!  This was a classic Attu experience, with teams of people assembling on a rare bird and maneuvering to get good views for everyone, although it took many hours to locate and assemble around the bird. Spotted Redshank is a rare migrant in the western Aleutians, primarily in spring where the Attu high count is four. Attu has but one previous fall record, from 26 Sep 2000. It has turned up rarely across the United States, in places like California, Massachusetts, and New Jersey, but is predictably seen only in Alaska. This was what we came here for. The grand Henderson Marsh stomp turned up other goodies as well. Chief among them was Wood Sandpiper, another rare Asian shorebird that was a life bird for most of the group. An eclipse-plumaged Eurasian Wigeon landed in Smew Pond with the redshank at one point, and a good number of Common Snipe (the Eurasian species recently split from Wilsons Snipe) were flushed by the various parties.  WEATHER: The weather today was, if anything, too nice. Sunny, temperatures in the upper 50s and low 60s, with very little wind. OTHER FAUNA: LEPS: PAINTED LADY - 1 (photo; first ever for Aleutians!). MAMMALS: Harbor Seal - x; Sea Otter - x; Minke Whale - x.		obs162787	Steven	Heinl	S10875062	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419985	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844395	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-18	07:30:00	Today got off to an early good start as well. Before most groups had even loaded Larry Balch called from Navy Town asking, "Does anyone want to see a Snowy Owl?" The Spotted Redshank was feeding in its "usual" spot and seemed to have become accustomed to groups of tourists gawking at it. We watched it spend about five minutes trying to swallow an oversized minnow that seemed to be stuck in its gullet. We were worried we might have to administer emergency care, but eventually the fish was swallowed and we can report that our redshank did live to see another day. Another massive rarity chase was set in motion when we glanced through the mist and fog to the back side of Smew Pond where a mid-sized shorebird was foraging. It turned out to be a juvenile Sharp-tailed Sandpiper, an Asian species that we had expected to see before this and which we began to worry that we would miss. Sharp-taileds are uncommon migrants throughout western Alaska, and can even be found predictably in the Pacific Northwest states during September and October, but which is accidental elsewhere in the country. It was a welcome lifer for much of the ship and so groups started converging on Smew Pond. Almost everyone got the bird immediately, but when one of the last groups arrived we had a bit of a scare. The Sharp-tailed flew upriver and was lost from sight for about 20 minutes. We tried to carefully walk the riverbed to flush the bird again and others of us carefully scanned the pond edge in case it had returned to its favored spots. Even when we knew where it was the Sharp-tailed had been very difficult to spot, and continuously moved in and out of the grasses at the edge. Perhaps it was not surprising then that the bird was missed. I had been the appointed riverwalker, and when I reached the pond I decided to try playing its call since it had earlier shown some level of tape response. As soon as I keyed up the iPod a shorebird started flying directly for me from the far side of the pond. It turned out to be the Sharp-tailed and on its return visit it gave great looks to the worried recent arrivals and lifted a great burden from the leaders' shoulders. We spent a long time absorbing its key field marks, which sunk in especially well for those of us that had carefully studied similar Pectoral Sandpipers in previous days. Several groups undertook ambitious afternoon walks. My group headed up Henderson Valley to Bird Canyon and Lake Elwood. Lake Elwood produced another new bird for the trip: an American Wigeon. This was perhaps the only time that I had seen Eurasian Wigeon (2) outnumber American (1), and it was one of the better comparative studies I have had. The gray head of the American contrasted markedly with its breast (little to no contrast on Eurasian). Almost on command, the American rose out of the water and flapped, revealing its diagnostic white underwing. Our other neat find on that long walk was a second Snowy Owl, this one a pure white adult sitting high on the rocky cliffs of Terrible Mountain. OTHER FAUNA: MAMMALS: Minke Whale; Harbor Seal; Sea Otter.		obs162787	Steven	Heinl	S10875069	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419988	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844534	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Ettienne Bay	L498125	H	52.9220479	172.6477432	2006-09-20	19:30:00	After enjoying the stint we hoofed it back to the boat and motored west to Etienne Bay. Thede Tobish had suggested to the team of leaders that we try Etienne as an alternate location to land. Since we had spent nearly a week in the Massacre Bay area we were happy for a change of pace, especially since Etienne was at the far southwestern tip and closer to arriving Asian birds Ettienne also had the allure of being unexplored by birders, so we were eager to put the place on the birding map. The trip west was fairly uneventful for seabirds, although I thoroughly enjoyed seeing a Parasitic Jaeger chase a Peregrine Falcon, then seeing the tables turn as the Peregrine chased the jaeger, and then seeing it switch again. One highlight as we entered Ettienne was a Whiskered Auklet that Steve Heinl spotted, which is known from just 2 prior Attu records. Ettienne Bay was fascinating in that the composition of seabirds was totally unlike that at Massacre Bay. Least Auklets were common in the mouth (we had none off Massacre). The eiders at Ettienne were mostly males, while in Massacre females predominated. And finally, we had loons: several species of loons. Steve Heinl (again) spotted a breeding plumaged Yellow-billed Loon at a distance but we motored slowly up to it and everyone got good looks. A second first-summer Yellow-billed was seen as well. And later, while the leaders scouted the shore for possible landing sites and birding areas, three Arctic Loons (adult and two juveniles) were spotted as well (I saw these well through the scope with Steve Heinl). When the birds were called into the ship only a few people were able to find these distant loons, but still, the different bird composition held exciting possibilities for the day that followed. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS127615984	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			1			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Kenai Peninsula	US-AK-122		Kachemak Bay	L653941	P	59.5677233	-151.5893555	2011-10-08	09:00:00	This is a field trip report for this falls Kachemak Bay Campus birding class.  This 4 hour boat trip started at the Homer Harbor, headed north along the Homer Spit to Mud Bay, then over to Gull Island, a bit into China Poot Bay, then Sixty-foot Rock, Cohen Island, Yukon Island, around Hesketh Island, and then back to the harbor.  In addition to seeing 28 species of birds we also saw 5 species of mammals; many sea otters, 5 river otters on Yukon Island, 1 harbor seal and 1 Steller's sea lion near Gull Island and a pod of about 10 humpback whales feeding and breeching in the outer part of Kachemak Bay.  Unusual bird sightings include 2 Pacific Wrens on Gull Island and a small flock of about 3 Fox Sparrows on Sixty-foot Rock.  The waterbird sightings were spread throughout the Bay, as you might expect.  Many species, particularly the murres and loons, seemed to be in molt.----Weather was very good for this time of the year.  It was in the upper 30s at the start of the trip and then warmed to the 40s.  Seas were calm and skies were mostly clear.		obs51101	George	Matz	S8917788	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD_AK	240	32.187		7	1		1	0

Unfortunately I slept through about 2 hours of Icy Strait but I was up and looking for birds the rest of the time. Aside from birds, we saw a lot of Sea Lions near Cape Spencer, humpback whales throughout the whole trip, and a pod of about 6 Killer Whales at the southern end of Icy Strait where it bumps into Admiralty Island. The weather was overcast and the water was fairly calm and smooth after we got out of the swells from the open ocean. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS42262926	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			1			United States	US	California	US-CA	Los Angeles	US-CA-037		Point Vicente	L324367	P	33.7414262	-118.4030378	2007-06-30	06:40:00	This morning I joined Kevin Larsen for a sea watch at Point Vicente.--We had been watching Sooty and small numbers of Pink-footed and--Black-vented Shearwaters flying west past the Point for about an hour--when Kevin said he was looking at an interesting alcid flying east down the coast. It took me a little while to get on the bird and just as I found it Kevin said he was looking at a Horned Puffin. I looked at it for a bit longer and told him that I agreed with his identification. We stayed on the bird discussing various field marks until it flew east and eventually out of sight. I also told him that it was identical in appearance to the two Horned Puffins I had seen at Leo carrillo State Beach on June 9. Kevin arrived about an hour earlier than me and had many more shearwaters and other birds that I did not include in this report.----Also present were two, and perhaps three, Blue Whales and a pod of about 12 Risso''s Dolphins.--		obs102836	Mike	San Miguel	S3000021	eBird - Stationary Count	EBIRD	150	0	0	2	1		1	1

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS42472157	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			1		Unknown Sex, Immature (1)	United States	US	California	US-CA	San Luis Obispo	US-CA-079		northcoastal SLO County	L342603	P	35.5716013	-121.1129021	2007-07-16	09:45:00	Aline Matsuo and I met Maggie Smith for a morning of birding along the northern coast of San Luis Obispo County with our primary target being the Horned Puffins that had been frequenting this part of the coast for nearly a month.  Although there were up to 7-10 birds seen in this region the previous month, it appears that a single bird has accounted for all sightings in the week prior to our sighting, and it is likely that this is the same bird that we saw.  We began our search at the viewing area with the lone cypress tree that is about a mile south of the Elephant Seal site.  After failing to locate any puffins here, we continued north to the Elephant Seal site, where I quickly located a puffin swimming offshore.  We then spent about the next 45 minutes observing and photographing this bird.  I also spent a short while scanning the inshore waters for other birds but not too much was evident.  After looking at the puffin, Aline and I visited Hearst Castle while Maggie headed south.  Following our quick visit to the castle visitors center, we stopped first to scan San Simeon Bay from the pier and then I quickly checked the mouth of San Simeon Creek, which had a little bit of water but not too many birds apart from gulls.  I spent little or no time looking at landbirds, so the few species that I did see were incidental and rather obvious.  We arrived soon after the fog cleared, so we had mostly clear but somewhat hazy skies, a mild breeze that increased to 10-15 knots from the northwest, and with temperatures ranging from the mid- to the upper 60s.  9:45-11:30 am (along the coast north of Hearst Castle) and ca. 12:15-1:00 pm (San Simeon Cove and mouth of San Simeon Creek).----California Ground-Squirrel - 10;--Northern Elephant Seal - 40 (calling);--Sea Otter - 2.		obs54638	Curtis	Marantz	S3015916	eBird - Casual Observation	EBIRD	150	8.047		3	1		1	1

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS42057109	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			2			United States	US	California	US-CA	San Mateo	US-CA-081	US-CA_119	Ano Nuevo SP	L109471	H	37.1207695	-122.3142672	2007-06-17		Spent most of the day prowling the bluffs at Ano Nuevo with my scope. Puffins, Brant and Oystercatchers were all just south of the park at the SMC/SCZ county line, at a point visible from the park. Both puffins were white-faced individuals. Ancient Murrelet, a life bird, floated by slowly on calm water just a hundred yards offshore giving extended opportunity for study of tiny, stubby pale bill, black chin above otherwise white underparts, clean white extending up across neck to a point behind the eye, dark gray back. Brown Pelican count is conservative; it was quite a show. Pelagic Cormorant count is even more conservative and is probably very low as birds were coming and going a lot. I did confirm 23 active PECO nests on the cliffs however, with sitting birds in place on the nests. There were probably more nests too; I was primarily in search of alcids and did not look as hard as I might have although the numbers given here are solid in terms of minimum numbers of confirmed individuals.		obs24619	Garth	Harwood	S2984566	eBird - Casual Observation	EBIRD					0		1	1

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS130018037	4624	species	Horned Puffin	Fratercula corniculata			1		Unknown Sex, Adult (1)	United States	US	Washington	US-WA	Grays Harbor	US-WA-027		Westport	L276529	H	46.9095527	-124.1167938	2007-07-21	14:50:00		At 1450, as our pelagic trip on the Monte Carlo was returning to port, we neared the outer end of the Westport jetty.   Seas were quite good here, with a small swell out of the south and less than 10 knots of wind.  The rain of earlier had momentarily diminished to a drizzle, skies were still heavily overcast so there was no glare.  George Gerdts, Brad Waggoner, Scott Mills and Bruce LaBar noted the puffin flying off the end of the jetty towards our boat.  It came along our starboard side at eye level, about 40 m distant, then turned off our stern and headed into the harbor along the jetty.  I had it in sight for about a half minute, and noted the following details through my Swarovski 10x42 EL binoculars.  ----A black and white alcid, larger than Rhinocerous Auklet and smaller than Common Murre, both of which were seen flying nearby for comparison.  Typical puffin wingbeat, less labored than murre or auklet.  Uppersurface entirely black.  Underparts mostly white, except dark wing linings and black collar across neck and chin.  Face largely white, shows a dark eye and narrow dark eyeline extending back from eye and narrow black 'horn' extending up from eye.  Beak massive, largely yellow with reddish at distal end.	obs115431	Bill	Tweit	S3018650	eBird - Stationary Count	EBIRD	30			22	0		1	1
